The default inputs parser<https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/parsers/parser-input-select.js#L18-L28> only handles text. I guess I could include an additional parser in the "parser-input-select.js" file for numeric only inputs (maybe of type number?).

$.tablesorter.addParser({

    id: "inputs-numeric",

    is: function(){

        return false;

    },

    format: function(s, table, cell) {

        var v = $(cell).find('input').val() || s,

            n = $.tablesorter.formatFloat((v || '').replace(/[^\w,. \-()]/g, ''), table);

        return n && typeof n === 'number' ? n : n ? $.trim( s && table.config.ignoreCase ? s.toLocaleLowerCase() : s ) : s;

    },

    parsed : true, // filter widget flag

    type: "numeric"

});

You can add the above widget, and load the "parser-input-select.js" file for the extra code to make this work.

—
Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub<https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/issues/888#issuecomment-97134884>.

@bkovacev I am on board with your suggestions with a `sensitive_fields` view setting.

One of the challenges that `_clean_data` has that Django's `_clean_credentials` does not have is control of the keys Django wants to clean. This is likely why Django opted for a regex. The key set is finite and controlled. `_clean_data` does not have that luxury but is still useful in providing security benefits.

@triat One way to get around case sensitivity issue is to force the case using `.lower()` or `.upper()`. That could be used on all the keys in the sensitive fields list used in `_clean_data` as well as the keys passed into `_clean_data` as an argument.

If you anyone here amends/updates this PR or another new one with the collaborated suggestions I can take a look and merge it in.

