Thank you for your input, and your effort.

I am a bit uncertain about what your problem is, however. As is documented [here](https://pynput.readthedocs.io/en/latest/mouse.html#handling-mouse-listener-errors) and [here](https://pynput.readthedocs.io/en/latest/keyboard.html#handling-keyboard-listener-errors), any errors raised by callback methods will be re-raised _when you join the listener_.

Since callbacks happen in a separate thread, and are initiated from the operating system, I cannot se any other way to do it. If you want immediate notification when your callback fails to handle an exception, you may want to wrap it thus:
```python
import logging

def log_exception(f):
    def inner(*args, **kwargs):
        try:
            return f(*args, **kwargs)
        except:
            logging.getLogger(f.__globals__['__name__']).exception(
                '%s failed to handle an exception', f.__name__)
    return inner

@log_exception
def my_monitor_callback(*args, **kwargs):
    """A callback for a keyboard monitor.
    """
    raise Exception('coffee!')
```

