To describe the implementation of `antireflect` in commit 71d36cd, refer to the following image where the original signal is indicated in red.  Vertical bars indicate points of anti-symmetry.
![antireflect](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6528957/36509175-d8e6406e-172c-11e8-9ae0-1f22fb1f232e.png)

The C code for extension immediately to the left of the `input` signal is given by:
```c
            // whole-sample anti-symmetric
            size_t k;
            TYPE le = input[0];    // current left edge value
            TYPE tmp = 0;
            while (j < F) {
                for(k = 1; k < N && j < F; ++j, ++k){
                    tmp = le - (input[k] - input[0]);
                    sum += filter[j]*tmp;
                }
                le = tmp;
                for(k = 1; k < N && j < F; ++j, ++k){
                    tmp = le + (input[N-1-k] - input[N-1]);
                    sum += filter[j]*tmp;
                }
                le = tmp;
            }
```
The first `for` loop covers the first segment between black vertical lines to the left of the red section.  The second `for` loop covers the second segment to the left of the red section.  The `while` loop then covers any additional segments to the left.  All of the symmetric and antisymmetric modes share this general structure.  Most often, in PyWavelets the signal is longer than the FIR filter for the wavelet so the second for loop and additional iterations of the while loop usually do not come into play. 

The value for the first black dot to the left of the red region should be the value at the edge point (`input[0]`) minus the difference between input[1] and input[0].
e.g.  `val = input[0] - (input[1] - input[0])`.  
This is what the first for loop is doing.

For subsequent reflections, the reflection is instead about the edge point from the prior reflection, so we need a variable, `le` (for left edge) here, to keep track of the current point we are reflecting about.  The difference terms such as `(input[k] - input[0])` stay the same for all reflections, just switching sign and iteration direction between the first and second for loops.  Put another way, within the `while` loop, the first `for` loop here covers any odd number of reflections while the second covers any even number of reflections.

There is a very similar while loops for extension from the right edge that operates on exactly the same principle.

